<html>
  <head>
    <title>Can I call it... <%= term %>?</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="style.css" media="screen" />
  <body>
    <div id="header">
      <form action="/" method="get">
        <h1>Can I Call It...
          <input type="text" name="search" value="<%= term %>" autofocus="autofocus"/>?
          <input type="submit" style="position: absolute; left: -9999px"/>
        </h1>
      </form>
    </div>
    <div id="result">
      <%= result %>
    </div>
    <div id="metadata">
      <p>This result was based on project data from <a href="https://github.com">Github</a>, <a href="http://sourceforge.net">SourceForge</a>, <a href="http://rubygems.org">Ruby Gems</a>, <a href="http://pypi.python.org">PyPI</a>, <a href="http://search.maven.org">Maven</a> and the <a href="https://admin.fedoraproject.org/pkgdb">Fedora PackageDB</a>.</p>
      <p>No checking is performed to find 'duplicate-ish' results, e.g. a Ruby Gem that uses Github for version control may be listed twice.</p>
      <p>Only Github repositories with >5 forks are considered 'significant' enough to worry about.</p>
    </div>
    <div id="footer">
      <p>"Can I Call It...?" is a simple script for checking if the name you'd like for your new, shiny project has already been used by somebody else.</p>
      <p>It was written by <a href="http://ianrenton.com">Ian Renton</a>. Source code is available on <a href="https://github.com/ianrenton/canicallit">Github</a> under the <a href="https://github.com/ianrenton/canicallit/blob/master/LICENCE.md">BSD licence</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>
